26 SECTION 2. REQUIRING A REPORT ON STATE VEHICLES. The Department of
27 Health and Welfare shall provide a report on vehicle resources within the
28 agency and proposed strategies and solutions to maximize vehicle use and
29 minimize costs. The report shall include utilization data and determina-
30 tions of whether vehicle count, allocation, and type are appropriate for
31 its operations with a focus on efficiency, economy, and cost effectiveness.
32 The format of the report and the content therein shall be determined by the
33 Budget and Policy Analysis Division of the Legislative Services Office and
34 shall be submitted to the Joint Finance-Appropriations Committee and the
35 Budget and Policy Analysis Division of the Legislative Services Office no
36 later than December 15, 2025.
37 SECTION 3. TRANSFER LIMITATION EXEMPTION. Notwithstanding any other
38 provisions of law to the contrary, the Licensing and Certification program

2
1 may transfer personnel costs pursuant to Section 67-3511, Idaho Code, for
2 the period July 1, 2025, through June 30, 2026.
3 SECTION 4. REQUIRING A REPORT ON THE TRANSITION OF LICENSING AND CER-
4 TIFICATION. The Department of Health and Welfare shall provide a report
5 outlining the steps necessary to transition the Division of Licensing and
6 Certification to the Division of Occupational and Professional Licenses
7 (DOPL). The Department of Health and Welfare shall collaborate with DOPL to
8 draft legislation that would enable the relocation of funding and staff, to
9 obtain necessary federal approvals, and on other considerations to facili-
10 tate a transition without interruption of public services. The report shall
11 be submitted to the Joint Finance-Appropriations Committee and the Budget
12 and Policy Analysis Division of the Legislative Services Office no later
13 than January 5, 2026.
14 SECTION 5. FEDERAL FUNDING RESTRICTIONS. Pursuant to Section
15 67-3511(2), Idaho Code, legislative appropriations shall not be transferred
16 from one fund to another fund unless expressly approved by the Legislature.
17 Appropriations made pursuant to this act contingent on anticipated federal
18 funding, grants, or programs shall not be supplanted by state funds in the
19 event of any reduction or elimination of such federal support without leg-
20 islative approval. The agency receiving the appropriation shall take all
21 necessary actions to ensure that the state is not obligated to replace lost
22 federal funds. Pursuant to Section 67-1917, Idaho Code, the agency will
23 submit an inventory of federal funds utilized by the agency. State funds ap-
24 propriated to satisfy match requirements for federal funds shall be reverted
25 to the maximum extent possible if federal funds requiring match is reduced
26 or eliminated. The agency shall promptly notify the Budget and Policy Anal-
27 ysis Division of the Legislative Services Office of any significant changes
28 related to federal funding, grants, or programs. This does not apply to
29 standard federal funding adjustments that take place within an agency's cost
30 allocation plan or indirect expenditure plan for indirect costs and agency
31 support staff, FMAP adjustments, or entitlement programs.
32 SECTION 6. CONDITIONS, LIMITATIONS, AND RESTRICTIONS. Appropriations
33 made pursuant to this act are subject to the conditions, limitations, and re-
34 strictions specified in this act.
35 SECTION 7. TRANSFER LIMITATION EXEMPTION. Notwithstanding any other
36 provisions of law to the contrary, the Licensing and Certification program
37 may transfer personnel costs pursuant to Section 67-3511, Idaho Code, for
38 the period July 1, 2024, through June 30, 2025.
39 SECTION 8. An emergency existing therefor, which emergency is hereby
40 declared to exist, Section 7 of this act shall be in full force and effect on
41 and after passage and approval, and Sections 1 through 6 of this act shall be
42 in full force and effect on and after July 1, 2025.

